42
00:02:40,319 --> 00:02:42,959
Other scientists double-checking the experiment

43
00:02:42,960 --> 00:02:45,200
to make sure everything was done correctly.

44
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:49,920
One way they do this is to duplicate or repeat the experiment

45
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:52,080
to see if they get the same result.

46
00:02:52,080 --> 00:02:57,280
In other words, Neil wants scientists to have crossed the teeth and dotted the eyes,

47
00:02:57,920 --> 00:03:02,879
a phrase which means paying attention to the small details of whatever you're doing.

48
00:03:02,879 --> 00:03:07,760
A scientific approach requires an open mind and critical thinking,

49
00:03:07,760 --> 00:03:12,879
but Neil believes the most important thing is to know the difference between fact and opinion.

50
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:18,719
People have opinions about all kinds of things, but that doesn't make what they believe a fact.

51
00:03:18,719 --> 00:03:22,960
Yet fact and opinion are becoming harder to separate,

52
00:03:22,960 --> 00:03:28,159
as protest by anti-vaccine groups and climate change deniers have shown,

53
00:03:28,159 --> 00:03:33,439
many Americans, even presidents, seem suspicious of scientific fact.

54
00:03:34,159 --> 00:03:39,280
It's a worrying trend that Neil thinks is a result of the US education system,

55
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:42,400
as he told BBC World Service Program Hard Talk.

56
00:03:43,599 --> 00:03:47,200
It has to do with how science is taught in the schools.

57
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:50,560
